Design hack: Use inexpensive materials creatively!  Here’s how I did this in my daughter’s bathroom remodel:

Countertops: the scalloped edge on plain, white quartz was only a $150 upgrade

Tile: Simple subway tile (@bedrosianstile Makoto Blush & Shoji White) in a fun pattern

Plumbing: All @deltafaucet (and I’ve showered in here and it’s 👌🏻)

Sconces: @mymitzi - a wonderful, affordable lighting brand
 
Cabinetry: Flat front is usually cheaper than shaker - and your eye needed the relief in here. Painted @farrowandball Peignoir

Shower curtain and Roman shade: my only splurge! @imogenheathinteriors 

Photographer: @nathanschroderphoto
Construction: @spruillremodel

I know the painted brick trend has some strong opponents, but this is one of my favorite before and after to-date.  Paint color: Benjamin Moore Seapearl with Benjamin Pashmina trend. 

Note: a common mistake I see with painted brick is using the trim color on the soffit and fascia.  The result is that your eye stops right at the roofline and, unless your house is 10 stories tall, makes it feel a little squat.  I always prefer painting the soffit and fascia the same color as the brick, creating the illusion that the house is taller than it is.  Kind of like a great pair of high heels 😉

Photographer: @nathanschroderphoto
